"title": "5338: holiday",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5338",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A day or period of time during which regular work is suspended. In Israel, the Sabbath provided a weekly break from everyday labour, giving opportunity for rest and religious assembly, and was the pattern for set days of rest and annual festivals. The NT records events in the life of Jesus Christ which are marked by Christian holidays.</p>\n<h2>The Sabbath day</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen2:2-Gen2:3\">GEN 2:2–2:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod31:13-Exod31:17\">EXO 31:13–31:17</a> <em>Their observance of the Sabbath marked Israel out as the distinctive people of God</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer17:24\">JER 17:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:27\">MRK 2:27</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb4:4\">HEB 4:4</a></p>\n<h2>The purpose of holidays</h2>\n<h3>For rest and refreshment</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod23:12\">EXO 23:12</a></strong> <em>The Sabbath provided a rest period each week.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod20:8-Exod20:11\">EXO 20:8–20:11</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut5:12-Deut5:14\">DEU 5:12–5:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod34:21\">EXO 34:21</a></p>\n<h3>To restore society</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev25:2-Lev25:5\">LEV 25:2–25:5</a> <em>The sabbath year allowed the land to be rested</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev25:10\">LEV 25:10</a> <em>The restoration of family property in the Year of Jubilee</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut15:12\">DEU 15:12</a> <em>The sabbath year marked the release of Hebrew slaves.</em></p>\n<h3>To assemble for worship</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:3\">LEV 23:3</a></strong> <em>Release from the ties of everyday labour gives opportunity for the people of God to meet together in worship</em>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num29:12\">NUM 29:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:27\">LEV 23:27</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num29:7\">NUM 29:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut16:8\">DEU 16:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa1:13\">ISA 1:13</a><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps42:4\">PSA 42:4</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps68:24-Ps68:27\">PSA 68:24–68:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps118:27\">PSA 118:27</a></p>\n<h3>To recall God's deliverance</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut5:15\">DEU 5:15</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut16:3\">DEU 16:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut16:12\">DEU 16:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb4:11\">HEB 4:11</a></p>\n<h2>Israel's seven annual holidays</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod12:16\">EXO 12:16</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:7-Lev23:8\">LEV 23:7–23:8</a> <em>the first and seventh days of the Feast of Unleavened Bread</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:21\">LEV 23:21</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num28:26\">NUM 28:26</a> <em>the day of firstfruits (Pentecost)</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:24-Lev23:25\">LEV 23:24–23:25</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num29:1\">NUM 29:1</a> <em>the Feast of Trumpets</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:28-Lev23:32\">LEV 23:28–23:32</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:29-Lev16:31\">LEV 16:29–16:31</a> <em>the Day of Atonement</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:34-Lev23:36\">LEV 23:34–23:36</a> <em>the first and eighth days of the Feast of Tabernacles</em></p>\n<h2>Christian holidays linked with the life of Jesus Christ</h2>\n<h3>The Lord's Day</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:7\">ACT 20:7</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark16:9\">MRK 16:9</a> <em>The church meets together on the first day of the week: the day of Jesus Christ's resurrection</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor16:2\">1CO 16:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev1:10\">REV 1:10</a></p>\n<h3>Christmas Day</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke2:7\">LUK 2:7</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:14\">JHN 1:14</a></p>\n<h3>Epiphany</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt2:1-Matt2:2\">MAT 2:1–2:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt2:9-Matt2:11\">MAT 2:9–2:11</a></p>\n<h3>Lent</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt4:1-Matt4:2\">MAT 4:1–4:2</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:12-Mark1:13\">MRK 1:12–1:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:1-Luke4:2\">LUK 4:1–4:2</a></p>\n<h3>Good Friday</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt27:45-Matt27:50\">MAT 27:45–27:50</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark15:33-Mark15:37\">MRK 15:33–15:37</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:44-Luke23:46\">LUK 23:44–23:46</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:28-John19:30\">JHN 19:28–19:30</a></p>\n<h3>Easter Sunday</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark16:5-Mark16:6\">MRK 16:5–16:6</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt28:5-Matt28:6\">MAT 28:5–28:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke24:4-Luke24:6\">LUK 24:4–24:6</a></p>\n<h3>Ascension Day</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke24:50-Luke24:51\">LUK 24:50–24:51</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts1:9\">ACT 1:9</a></p>\n<h3>Pentecost (Whit Sunday)</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:1-Acts2:4\">ACT 2:1–2:4</a></p>",
